---
# Raw Experimental Traces
Before fitting the model, it is instructive to visualize the raw experimental data. The plots below show all recorded action potential traces for each experimental group, overlaid to show the degree of variation.

```julia; echo=false
println("Generating raw trace plots...")
for (group_name, file) in zip(group_names_for_report, trace_files)
    
    #display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("## Group: `$group_name`\n")))
    
    filepath = joinpath(data_folder, file)
    if isfile(filepath)
        df_raw = CSV.read(filepath, DataFrame; header=4, missingstring="")
        raw_plot = ActionPotentialPlots.plot_raw_traces(df_raw, group_name)
        savefig(raw_plot, joinpath(images_dir, "raw_traces_$(group_name).png"))
        display(raw_plot)
    else
        println("*Data file not found for group $(group_name): $(filepath)*")
    end
end
```
---

# Individual Trace Analysis
The model was first fitted to individual action potential traces from each experimental group.  

The plots below show the final fitted model trace (blue) overlaid on the experimental data (red) for each recording.  
The stimulus current used by the model is shown on the right-hand axis (green).

```julia; echo=false
println("Searching for individual trace plots...")
for (group_name, file) in zip(group_names_for_report, trace_files)
    #display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("## Group: `$group_name`\n")))
    
    output_dir = joinpath(output_folder, "Trace", "latest")

    raw_data_path = joinpath(data_folder, file)
    num_traces_in_file = 0
    if isfile(raw_data_path)
        df_raw = CSV.read(raw_data_path, DataFrame; header=4, missingstring="")
        num_traces_in_file = Int(ncol(df_raw) / 2)
    end
    
    # Find all plot files for the current group
    plot_files_for_group = []
    for i in 1:num_traces_in_file # Assuming max 9 traces
        plot_filename = "$(replace(file, ".csv" => ""))_trace_$(i)_fit.png"
        plot_path = joinpath(output_dir, plot_filename)
        if isfile(plot_path)
            push!(plot_files_for_group, plot_path)
        end
    end

    if !isempty(plot_files_for_group)
        # Load each PNG and create a plot object from it, removing axes and borders
        image_plots = [plot(load(f), axis=nothing, border=:none) for f in plot_files_for_group]
        
        # Determine a nice grid layout (e.g., 3 columns)
        num_plots = length(image_plots)
        layout_cols = 3
        layout_rows = ceil(Int, num_plots / layout_cols)
        
        # Create the final grid plot for this group
        grid_plot = plot(image_plots..., 
                         layout=(layout_rows, layout_cols), 
                         size=(1200, 350 * layout_rows), # Adjust size as needed
                         plot_title="Individual Fits: $(group_name)")
        
        # Display the single grid plot for this group
        savefig(grid_plot, joinpath(images_dir, "individual_fits_$(group_name).png"))
        display(grid_plot)
    else
        println("*No plot files found for group $(group_name) in '$(output_dir)'. Please run the 'traces' workflow.*")
    end
end
```

---

# Group Analysis & Statistical Comparison
A group-level analysis was performed to compare the model parameters across the different experimental conditions (WT, P, EPN).  
This involved thousands of model fits initiated from different starting conditions to robustly explore the parameter space.

---

## Parameter Distributions
The box plots below show the distribution of the final fitted values for each optimized parameter, separated by experimental group.  
This visualization helps identify which parameters are significantly altered by the experimental conditions.

```julia; echo=false
# Generate and display box plots
if sim_data !== nothing
    boxplot_fig = ActionPotentialPlots.plot_param_boxplots(sim_data, opt_par_names)
    boxplot_path = joinpath(images_dir, "summary_boxplots.png")
    savefig(boxplot_fig, boxplot_path)

    display(boxplot_fig)
else
    println("*Group analysis data is missing, skipping box plots.*")
end
```


---

## Average Model Behavior
To visualize the functional consequences of the parameter shifts,  
we simulated the model using the average fitted parameters for each group.  

The plot below shows the resulting average action potential for each condition.

```julia; echo=false
# Generate and display average traces
if sim_data !== nothing
    average_model_fig = ActionPotentialPlots.plot_average_traces(sim_data)
    average_model_path = joinpath(images_dir, "summary_average_models.png")
    savefig(average_model_fig, average_model_path)
    
    display(average_model_fig)
else
    println("*Group analysis data is missing, skipping average traces plot.*")
end
```

---

# Statistical Modeling
To formally test for differences, a linear mixed-effects model was fitted for each parameter.  

- Experimental group = fixed effect  
- Initial parameter randomization (`tbl`) = random effect  

The model summaries are below.

```julia; echo=false
# Run and display mixed-effects models
if sim_data !== nothing
    for param in opt_par_names
        # Section header
        display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("### Analysis for Parameter: `$param`\n")))

        try
            formula = @eval @formula($param ~ 1 + group + (1 + group | tbl))
            model = fit(MixedModel, formula, sim_data)
            
            # Capture model summary
            io = IOBuffer()
            show(io, MIME("text/plain"), model)
            model_output = String(take!(io))

            # Display summary as fenced code block in Markdown
            display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("```julia\n$model_output\n```")))
        catch e
            display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("> Could not fit model for `$param`. Error: `$e`")))
        end
    end
else
    println("*Group analysis data is missing, skipping statistical models.*")
end
```

# Parameter Correlation and Variability
This section provides additional statistical analysis on the fitted parameters from the group workflow to assess parameter identifiability.

```julia; echo=false
if sim_data !== nothing
    # --- Coefficient of Variation Analysis ---
    display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("## Coefficient of Variation (CV)\n\nThe table below shows the CV for each parameter within each experimental group. Lower values suggest the parameter is more consistently identified by the optimizer.\n")))
    
    cv_df = combine(groupby(sim_data, :group)) do sdf
        cvs = (param => Statistics.std(sdf[!, param]) / Statistics.mean(sdf[!, param]) for param in opt_par_names)
        return (; group=first(sdf.group), cvs...)
    end
    display(cv_df)

    # --- Pairwise Correlation Analysis ---
    display(Markdown.MD(Markdown.parse("\n## Pairwise Parameter Correlations\n\nThe scatter plots below show pairwise correlations between fitted parameters, colored by experimental group. Strong correlations can indicate issues with parameter identifiability.\n")))
    
    # Call the plotting function from the plots module
    pairwise_fig = ActionPotentialPlots.plot_pairwise_params(sim_data, opt_par_names)
    pairwise_path = joinpath(images_dir, "pairwise_comparisons.png")
    savefig(pairwise_fig, pairwise_path)
    display(pairwise_fig)
else
    println("*Group analysis data is missing, skipping advanced statistical analysis.*")
end
```

---

# Conclusion
This automated analysis provides a comprehensive overview of the model fitting results,  
highlighting key differences in ion channel parameters between experimental groups.
